32 rips around the sun today, and it has been a damn good one! We brought our first child into the world, and I became Nash D’s daddy! We won the freakin US NATIONALS! Was on the cover of @dragillustrated ! Obtained my top alcohol dragster license! Won enough $ with Beer Money that I’m still drinking Yuengling off of it, and so much more! 

I’m living a life that most dream of, and while sometimes I get caught up in the day to day, I’m very thank ful for all of those who have supported, sacrificed, and loved me along the way! I didn’t get here on my own, and for that I’m forever grateful! 32 is shaping up to be a big one, and I can’t wait to share our plans! Chutes out, visors down! LETS GOOO!!!

First round finish line cam, this past Saturday, at Rockingham, for Turbo John’s Mid Track no prep race. 

Unfortunately at the 2-3 shift, during this run, we had some engine parts failure, and we were unable to make next round. We had almost 500 runs on this rotating assembly, and ol girl was tired! 

Pretty amazing what off the shelf LS platform parts are capable of. Still the same stock GM 6.2 aluminum block we started with, and we will continue with it until it waves the white flag too! 

A quick refresh at Harrell Engine and Dyno, and we’ll be back!!!

#beermoney

Dr. John Mayer, clinical psychologist at Doctor on Demand, told NBC News that seeing Beer Money triggers your flight-or-fight and survival instincts, which is why you're drawn to the destruction.

"A disaster enters into your awareness. This can be from a live source such as driving by a traffic accident, from watching Beer Money make a pass, a plane crash, or any disaster," he explains to NBC News. "This data from our perceptual system then stimulates the amygdala (the part of the brain responsible for emotions, survival tactics, and memory). The amygdala then sends signals to the regions of the frontal cortex that are involved in analyzing and interpreting data. Next, the brain evaluates whether this data (awareness of the disaster such as Beer Money) is a threat to you; thus judgment gets involved. As a result, the 'fight or flight' response is evoked."

Just to set a couple things straight, when discussions with TSR first took place, Tony had very little seat time in a drag car period. When making a driver change like this, there are so many moving pieces! At that time, Tony did not feel as though he could comfortably make a full-time commitment, so Leah and the team moved forward with plans for me to fill the seat. 

Tony had a breakout season last year, and proved that he was more than ready to step out of the alcohol dragster, and into the top fuel car. At the end of the day, he owns the car, and collectively if they feel he is ready, then he should drive the car!

I am so honored to have been their choice to represent TSR in Top fuel! If I never get the chance to drive one again, I can hang my hat on the fact that I was that close! 

I wish them nothing but the best in 2024 and beyond. Smoke, if you decide to step out, you have my number! ￼
